## Production rule of thumb

If your application logic broadcasts in PARALLEL (e.g., a server-side process emits to many topics in `Promise.all`, or a UI causes many simultaneous user actions), expect to encounter the rate-limit return value. Handle it:

```ts
async function sendWithRetry(ch: RealtimeChannel, msg: BroadcastMsg, maxRetries = 3) {
  for (let attempt = 0; attempt < maxRetries; attempt++) {
    const r = await ch.send(msg);
    if (r === 'ok') return r;
    if (r === 'rate limited') {
      await new Promise(res => setTimeout(res, 100 * Math.pow(2, attempt)));
      continue;
    }
    return r; // other unexpected return — propagate
  }
  throw new Error('send: rate limited after retries');
}
```

If your application is naturally serial (one user action → one broadcast), you won't hit the limit at typical volumes.

